<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-785-006  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 785 006.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  August 20 1990 v36 n1823 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>SEMI asks CoCom to ease gear reins. (Semiconductor Equipment andamp;Materials International asks the Coordinating Committee onMultilateral Export Controls to lift export controls onsemiconductor production equipment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Semiconductor Equipment andamp; Materials International (SEMI) submits arecommendation to the Coordinating Committee on MultilateralExport Controls (CoCom) that export controls on semiconductorproduction equipment able to fabricate devices with linewidths ofone micron or more be lifted.andP;  SEMI Pres William Reed says it wasappropriate to send the recommendation to CoCom rather than to theUS government because SEMI is an international group.andP;  The USgovernment has consistently supported retention of tight exportcontrols on semiconductor equipment and materials.andP;  SEMI suggeststhat CoCom controls on fabrication equipment and materials be tieddirectly to semiconductor controls, which SEMI members claim is afar simpler way to administer CoCom controls on semiconductorequipment.andP;  The SEMI plan would remove controls on productionequipment to 1.23-micron levels, which is the level of 256K DRAMdevices, and would allow for automatic indexing of relaxedequipment controls.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradePolitical IssuesExportRegulationTrade and Professional AssociationsProposalSemiconductor production equipmentCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsSemiconductor Equipment and Materials International.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>